                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14476439" author="blackdrag" created="Fri, 15 Aug 2014 03:56:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;italics means the compiler did not find a local variable or field for it. It is no error in Groovy unless you use the static compiler. Groovy is a dynamic language after all and allows you to add properties at runtime through meta programming. Thus not showing this as an error is no bug. That you have to prefix is though&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14480692" author="mitsu" created="Fri, 15 Aug 2014 09:42:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;No, you are wrong. Come on, if you&apos;re going to comment on a ticket, at least pay attention and write something accurate. Please do not explain the obvious, especially when you are incorrect.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Italics does NOT mean the compiler did not find a local variable or field for it. Do you even use STS? Italics means the compiler DID find the field. Underline means the compiler did not find the field. The field is italicized and in blue &amp;#8212; which means it recognizes it as a field. Go back and actually use STS. Check before you post.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14480665" author="mitsu" created="Fri, 15 Aug 2014 09:48:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;To be more clear about STS: Italics means the IDE thinks the field is a static member. Blue means the IDE thinks the field is defined (and not dynamic). Underline means the IDE did not find the field. The IDE thinks it is a valid field reference, but it fails at runtime.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14476389" author="blackdrag" created="Fri, 15 Aug 2014 18:57:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Looks like I remembered it wrong then. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14476371" author="blackdrag" created="Mon, 18 Aug 2014 10:15:08 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Looking at this further it seems that the inner enum does not get the dispatcher methods for inner classes.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17755535" author="emilles" created="Thu, 17 Aug 2023 12:48:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/groovy/commit/1ea6927ad9c6ec7e05266e1385e3787866c888ad&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/groovy/commit/1ea6927ad9c6ec7e05266e1385e3787866c888ad&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
